My experience was fine.  I've been disappointed in Scholastic's response or lack of response to my feedback on the lack of support for teachers who work in low income buildings.  Teaching in a high poverty school, my students never order from Scholastic.  As a matter of fact, I'm ordering with my own money so that I can send books home to these students who have none in their homes.  In order to "open" your one dollar book store I have to spend a significant amount of money ($75 now, $100 in the fall and in previous years).  It seems that teachers who work in title 1 schools should be able to order one dollar books automatically no matter how much money is spent.  My colleagues that teach in higher socioeconomic schools are receiving all kinds of wonderful items they can buy with their bonus points for their classrooms.  I am using my own money and bonus points to buy books for students.  I am then having to buy anything special for my classroom from my own pocket also.  Where is the equity?

Additional Comments: My students are fifth graders. They are starting to notice that the quality of the toy oriented items are pretty poor. A number of my students ordered a techdeck product recently and were disappointed that the "table" they got to do tricks on was cardboard and broke quickly compared to the ones they buy in store that are plastic and sturdy. Because they are "catalog ordering" they are not savvy enough to expect a mediocre product. The same thing happens with some of the necklace and bracelet options. Overall the products are cheaply made, and definitely not the best value when compared to the price of the good books you have for sale.
